docs.lead_paragraph: Jill Biden laid out the political calculus of her husband’s presidential campaign in extraordinarily blunt terms on Monday, directly acknowledging that some voters may prefer other candidates but urging them to support Joseph R. Biden Jr. anyway, in an effort to defeat President Trump.

headline.print_headline: Jill Biden Asks Some Primary Voters to ‘Swallow’ Their First Choice

docs.abstract: Ms. Abrams, who announced this week that she would not run for president, told The New York Times that she would be “honored to be considered” for vice president.
docs.snippet: Ms. Abrams, who announced this week that she would not run for president, told The New York Times that she would be “honored to be considered” for vice president.
docs.lead_paragraph: Stacey Abrams made it official this week that she would not seek the presidency after months of speculation among Democrats, becoming one of the most prominent party leaders to pass on the 2020 race. But in an interview Tuesday night, she said she was open to being considered for the No. 2 spot by “any nominee.”

headline.main: Stacey Abrams Says She’s Open to Being Vice President for Any Democratic Nominee
headline.print_headline: Not in the Running, but Open To ‘Other Political Opportunities’

headline.main: Why Is Cory Booker Spending So Much Time in These 3 Cities?

docs.abstract: Joe Biden said there was no room for compromise with congressional Republicans, while Elizabeth Warren sounded more open to it and wanted a broad solution to gun violence.
docs.snippet: Joe Biden said there was no room for compromise with congressional Republicans, while Elizabeth Warren sounded more open to it and wanted a broad solution to gun violence.
docs.lead_paragraph: CEDAR RAPIDS, Iowa — Joe Biden and Elizabeth Warren, two of the leading candidates for the 2020 Democratic nomination, made the case on Monday for muscular new gun control proposals, but differed on whether it was possible to reach compromise with congressional Republicans.

docs.abstract: As Democrats gather for the next presidential debates this week, several are struggling with fund-raising. An accounting maneuver last month made some appear to have more cash on hand than they did.
docs.snippet: As Democrats gather for the next presidential debates this week, several are struggling with fund-raising. An accounting maneuver last month made some appear to have more cash on hand than they did.
docs.lead_paragraph: Staff members for a half dozen Democratic presidential candidates did not receive their final June paycheck that month. Instead, their campaigns nudged payday into July, an accounting maneuver that obscured payroll costs and temporarily made it look like candidates had more cash on hand than they actually did.

headline.main: Low in Cash and Polls, 2020 Democrats Get Creative With Accounting
headline.print_headline: Down in Polls and Fund-Raising, Candidates Get Creative With Finances

docs.abstract: As the next debates loom, the progressive wing of the party wants sweeping change. Many others just want to jettison the president.
docs.snippet: As the next debates loom, the progressive wing of the party wants sweeping change. Many others just want to jettison the president.
docs.lead_paragraph: WAUKEE, Iowa — Bernie Sanders preaches “political revolution” to the crowds at his campaign rallies. Elizabeth Warren promises “big, systemic change” as she rolls out major policy proposals. And Pete Buttigieg warns his packed town hall audiences that the “riskiest thing we could do is try too hard to play it safe.”

headline.main: Why Democrats Are So Far From Consensus on 2020
headline.print_headline: A Clash of Democratic Priorities: Change Presidents, or Change the Paradigm?

byline.original: By Reid J. Epstein and Lisa Lerer
